---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import { isBlogPublished } from '../../lib/blogGate';
import BlogCrossLinks from '../../components/BlogCrossLinks.astro';

const slug = Astro.url.pathname.replace('/blog/', '').replace(/\/$/, '');
const isPublished = await isBlogPublished(slug);
if (!isPublished) return Astro.redirect('/404');
---

<Layout title="Wind Speed: Knots to mph for Sailors and Pilots" description="Wind speed in knots to mph and km/h. Understand the Beaufort scale and what wind speeds mean for sailing and flying." keywords="knots to mph, wind speed conversion, beaufort scale, knots speed, sailing wind speed, aviation knots, wind speed chart">
  <div class="max-w-3xl">
    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert prose-gray max-w-none">
      <nav class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-6 not-prose">
        <a href="/blog" class="hover:text-amber-600">Blog</a> <span class="mx-1">›</span> <span class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300">Speed</span>
      </nav>
      <BlogCrossLinks title="Wind Speed: Knots to mph for Sailors and Pilots" />
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-8">June 26, 2025 • 4 min read</p>

      <p>Weather reports for sailors and pilots always give wind speed in knots. If you are used to mph or km/h, here is how to make sense of these measurements and understand what they mean for conditions on the water or in the air.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-1">The Conversion</h2>
      <div class="bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-900/20 border border-amber-200 dark:border-amber-800 rounded-xl p-5 my-6 not-prose">
        <p class="text-center text-lg font-mono font-bold text-amber-700 dark:text-amber-400">1 knot = 1.151 mph = 1.852 km/h</p>
        <p class="text-center text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mt-2">1 knot = 1 nautical mile per hour</p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-1">Quick Conversion Reference</h2>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>5 knots = 5.8 mph = 9.3 km/h (light breeze)</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>10 knots = 11.5 mph = 18.5 km/h (gentle breeze)</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>15 knots = 17.3 mph = 27.8 km/h (moderate breeze)</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>20 knots = 23.0 mph = 37.0 km/h (fresh breeze)</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>30 knots = 34.5 mph = 55.6 km/h (near gale)</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>50 knots = 57.5 mph = 92.6 km/h (storm)</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span>64 knots = 73.6 mph = 118.5 km/h (hurricane threshold)</span>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-1">The Beaufort Scale</h2>
      <p>Admiral Sir Francis Beaufort created this scale in 1805 to standardise wind observations at sea:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Force 0 (0-1 kt):</strong> Calm — mirror-like sea</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Force 3 (7-10 kt):</strong> Gentle breeze — good sailing for beginners</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Force 5 (17-21 kt):</strong> Fresh breeze — whitecaps, moderate waves</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Force 7 (28-33 kt):</strong> Near gale — sea heaps up, foam streaks</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Force 9 (41-47 kt):</strong> Strong gale — high waves, spray affects visibility</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Force 12 (64+ kt):</strong> Hurricane — devastation</span>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-1">What Wind Speeds Mean in Practice</h2>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Sailing (dinghy):</strong> Ideal conditions 8-15 knots; dangerous above 25 knots</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Sailing (yacht):</strong> Comfortable at 10-20 knots; reef sails above 25 knots</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Light aircraft:</strong> Crosswind limit typically 15-20 knots</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Commercial aircraft:</strong> Crosswind limit around 30-40 knots depending on aircraft</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Kite surfing:</strong> Needs at least 12 knots; ideal 15-25 knots</span>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-1">Why Knots and Not mph?</h2>
      <p>Since a knot is one nautical mile per hour, and nautical miles relate directly to degrees of latitude on charts, using knots makes navigation calculations simpler. An aircraft flying at 120 knots covers 2 degrees of latitude per hour — that is easy to plot on a chart without any conversion.</p>

      <div class="border-t border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800 mt-10 pt-8 not-prose">
        <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-4">Try It Now</h3>
        <a href="/convert/speed" class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-4 py-2 rounded-lg bg-amber-500 text-white text-sm font-semibold hover:bg-amber-600 transition-colors">Open Speed Converter →</a>
      </div>
    
      <div class="not-prose mt-8 p-4 bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-900/20 border border-amber-200 dark:border-amber-800 rounded-xl">
        <p class="text-sm text-amber-800 dark:text-amber-300 font-medium">🔗 Try our converter: <a href="/convert/speed" class="text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 font-bold hover:underline">Open Converter →</a></p>
      </div>
    </article>
  </div>
</Layout>
